IE6400 Foundations for Data Analytics Engineering¶

Fall 2023¶

Module 1: Basic of Python - Part 1¶

What is Python?¶

Python is a computer language that many people like to use. It was made by a person named Guido van Rossum and was introduced in 1991. People use Python for many things, and one of those things is working with data.

In Data Analytics Engineering, Python is an extremely valuable tool. Here are some of the key reasons why Python is widely used in this field:

  • Rich Ecosystem: Python has a vast ecosystem of libraries and frameworks that cater to data analytics and engineering needs. Some of the most popular ones include Pandas, NumPy, SciPy, Matplotlib, Seaborn, and Scikit-learn. These libraries provide data manipulation, analysis, visualization, and machine learning capabilities.

  • Data Processing and Transformation: Python is excellent for data preprocessing and transformation tasks. Pandas, in particular, is a powerful library for working with structured data, allowing you to read, manipulate, and clean data efficiently.

  • Data Visualization: Python offers a range of libraries for data visualization, such as Matplotlib and Seaborn. These tools make it easy to create informative plots and charts to understand and communicate insights from data.

  • Statistical Analysis: Python's SciPy library provides a wide array of statistical functions and tools for conducting statistical analysis, hypothesis testing, and other statistical operations.

  • Machine Learning: Python is a dominant language in the field of machine learning and artificial intelligence. Libraries like Scikit-learn, TensorFlow, and PyTorch are widely used for building and training machine learning models.

  • Big Data Processing: Python can be used in conjunction with big data processing frameworks like Apache Spark and Hadoop through libraries like PySpark. This allows for the processing and analysis of large datasets.

  • Database Connectivity: Python provides various libraries and packages for connecting to databases, including SQLAlchemy and psycopg2, making it easy to extract and load data from different data sources.

  • Integration with Other Tools: Python can easily integrate with other data engineering tools and platforms, such as Apache Airflow for workflow automation and data pipeline management.

  • Community and Documentation: Python has a large and active community of data analysts and engineers. This means that there is a wealth of documentation, tutorials, and community support available for anyone working in data analytics engineering.

  • Cross-Platform Compatibility: Python is a cross-platform language, making it suitable for various operating systems, which is essential in a diverse data engineering environment.

Python is like a trusty toolbox for people who work with data. It helps you clean, organize, and understand your data, and it's a popular choice among people who do this kind of work.

1. Variables¶

Variables are containers for storing data values.

Exercise 1.1 Creating Variables and Output Variables¶

Python has no command for declaring a variable.

A variable is created the moment you first assign a value to it.

In [1]:
x = 1 # x is of type int
print(x)

1
In [2]:
y = "NEU" # y is now of type str
print(y)

NEU
In [3]:
x = "University"
print("Northeastern " + x)

Northeastern University

For numbers, the + character works as a mathematical operator:

In [4]:
x = 5
y = 10
print(x + y)

15

You can use the + operator to output multiple variables:

In [5]:
x = "Northeastern "
y = "University"
z =  x + y
print(z)

Northeastern University

Notice the space character after "Northeastern " and "University", without them the result would be "NortheasternUniversity".

In the print() function, you output multiple variables, separated by a comma:

In [6]:
x = "Data"
y = "Analytics"
z = "Engineering"

print(x, y, z)

Data Analytics Engineering
In [7]:
x = 5
y = "John"
print(x, y)

5 John

The best way to output multiple variables in the print() function is to separate them with commas, which even support different data types.

print(x)

x = str("S1") # x will be 's1'
y = str(2)    # y will be '2'

print(x)

print(z)

Exercise 1.4 Single or Double Quotes?¶

String variables can be declared either by using single or double quotes:

In [17]:
x = "John"
print(x)
# double quotes are the same as single quotes:
x = 'John'
print(x)

John

Exercise 1.5 Case-Sensitive¶

Variable names are case-sensitive.

In [18]:
a = 4
A = "Sally"

print(a)
print(A)

4
Sally

The result showed that 'A' would not overwrite 'a'

Exercise 1.6 Many Values to Multiple Variables¶

Python allows you to assign values to multiple variables in one line:

In [19]:
x, y, z = "Orange", "Banana", "Cherry"

print(x)
print(y)
print(z)

Orange
Banana
Cherry

Make sure the number of variables matches the number of values, or else you will get an error.

Exercise 1.7 One Value to Multiple Variables¶

And you can assign the same value to multiple variables in one line:

In [20]:
x = y = z = "Orange"

print(x)
print(y)
print(z)

Orange
Orange
Orange

Exercise 1.8 Unpack a Collection¶

If you have a collection of values in a list, tuple etc. Python allows you to extract the values into variables. This is called unpacking.

In [21]:
fruits = ["apple", "banana", "cherry"]
x, y, z = fruits

print(fruits)
print(x)
print(y)
print(z)

['apple', 'banana', 'cherry']
apple
banana
cherry

2. Global Variables¶

Variables that are created outside of a function (as in all of the examples above) are known as global variables.

Global variables can be used by everyone, both inside of functions and outside.

Exercise 1.9 Create a variable outside of a function, and use it inside the function¶

In [22]:
x = "University"

def myfunc():
    print("Northeastern " + x)

myfunc()

Northeastern University

If you create a variable with the same name inside a function, this variable will be local, and can only be used inside the function. The global variable with the same name will remain as it was, global and with the original value.

In [23]:
x = "University"

def myfunc():
    x = "College"
    print("Northeastern " + x)

myfunc()

print("Northeastern " + x)

Northeastern College
Northeastern University

Exercise 1.10 The global Keyword¶

Normally, when you create a variable inside a function, that variable is local, and can only be used inside that function.

To create a global variable inside a function, you can use the global keyword.

If you use the global keyword, the variable belongs to the global scope:

In [24]:
def myfunc():
    global x
    x = "University"

myfunc()

print("Northeastern " + x)

Northeastern University

Also, use the global keyword if you want to change a global variable inside a function.

To change the value of a global variable inside a function, refer to the variable by using the global keyword:

In [25]:
x = "College"

def myfunc():
    global x
    x = "University"

myfunc()

print("Northeastern " + x)

Northeastern University

3. Python Strings¶

Strings in python are surrounded by either single quotation marks, or double quotation marks.

'hello' is the same as "hello".

Exercise 1.11 Multiline Strings¶

You can assign a multiline string to a variable by using three quotes:

In [26]:
a = """DAE Program,
Northeastern University,
Boston Campus
USA."""

print(a)

DAE Program,
Northeastern University,
Boston Campus
USA.

Or three single quotes:

In [27]:
a = '''DAE Program,
Northeastern University,
Boston Campus
USA.'''

print(a)

DAE Program,
Northeastern University,
Boston Campus
USA.

In the result, the line breaks are inserted at the same position as in the code.

Exercise 1.12 Strings are Arrays¶

Like many other popular programming languages, strings in Python are arrays of bytes representing unicode characters.

However, Python does not have a character data type, a single character is simply a string with a length of 1.

Square brackets can be used to access elements of the string.

Get the character at position 13 (remember that the first character has the position 0):

In [28]:
a = "Northeastern University"
print(a[13])

U

Exercise 1.13 Looping Through a String¶

Since strings are arrays, we can loop through the characters in a string, with a for loop.

Loop through the letters in the word "NORTHEASTERN":

In [29]:
for x in "NORTHEASTERN":
    print(x)

N
O
R
T
H
E
A
S
T
E
R
N

Exercise 1.14 String Length¶

To get the length of a string, use the len() function.

The len() function returns the length of a string:

In [30]:
a = "NORTHEASTERN"
print(len(a))

12

Exercise 1.15 Check String¶

To check if a certain phrase or character is present in a string, we can use the keyword in.

Check if "Engineering" is present in the following text:

In [31]:
txt = "Data Analytics Engineering"
print("Engineering" in txt)

True

Use it in an if statement:

Print only if "Engineering" is present:

In [32]:
txt = "Data Analytics Engineering"
if "Engineering" in txt:
    print("Yes, 'Engineering' is present.")

Yes, 'Engineering' is present.

Exercise 1.16 Check if NOT¶

To check if a certain phrase or character is NOT present in a string, we can use the keyword not in.

Check if "NEU" is NOT present in the following text:

In [33]:
txt = "Data Analytics Engineering"
print("NEU" not in txt)

True

Use it in an if statement:

print only if "NEU" is NOT present:

In [34]:
txt = "Data Analytics Engineering"
if "NEU" not in txt:
    print("No, 'NEU' is NOT present.")

No, 'NEU' is NOT present.

Exercise 1.16 Slicing Strings¶

You can return a range of characters by using the slice syntax.

Specify the start index and the end index, separated by a colon, to return a part of the string.

Get the characters from position 7 to position 12:

In [35]:
b = "Hello, World!"
print(b[7:12])

World

Note: The first character has an index of 0. The end position is not included.

Exercise 1.17 Slice From the Start¶

By leaving out the start index, the range will start at the first character:

Get the characters from the start to position 5

In [36]:
b = "Hello, World!"
print(b[:5])

Hello

Exercise 1.18 Slice To the End¶

By leaving out the end index, the range will go to the end:

Get the characters from position 15, and all the way to the end:

In [37]:
b = "Hello, World!"
print(b[7:])

World!

Exercise 1.19 Negative Indexing¶

Use negative indexes to start the slice from the end of the string:

Get the characters:

From: "A" in "DataAnalyticsEngineering" (position -20)

To, but not included: "E" in "DataAnalyticsEngineering" (position -11):

In [38]:
b = "DataAnalyticsEngineering"
print(b[-20:-11])

Analytics

Exercise 1.20 Modify Strings¶

Python has a set of built-in methods that you can use on strings.

Upper Case¶

The upper() method returns the string in upper case:

In [39]:
a = "Northeastern University"
print(a.upper())

NORTHEASTERN UNIVERSITY

Lower Case¶

The lower() method returns the string in lower case:

In [40]:
a = "NORTHEASTERN UNIVERSITY"
print(a.lower())

northeastern university

Remove Whitespace¶

Whitespace is the space before and/or after the actual text, and very often you want to remove this space.

The strip() method removes any whitespace from the beginning or the end:

In [41]:
a = "  Northeastern University   "
print(a)
print(a.strip())

  Northeastern University   
Northeastern University

Note that strip does not remove whitespace everywhere, only at the beginning and end.

Replace String¶

The replace() method replaces a string with another string:

In [42]:
a = "Northeastern University"
print(a.replace("University", "College"))

Northeastern College

Split String¶

The split() method returns a list where the text between the specified separator becomes the list items.

The split() method splits the string into substrings if it finds instances of the separator:

In [43]:
a = "DAE,Northeastern University"
print(a.split(","))

['DAE', 'Northeastern University']

Exercise 1.21 String Concatenation¶

To concatenate, or combine, two strings you can use the + operator.

In [44]:
a = "Northeastern"
b = "University"
c = a + b
print(c)

NortheasternUniversity

To add a space between them, add a " ":

In [45]:
a = "Northeastern"
b = "University"
c = a + " " + b
print(c)

Northeastern University

Exercise 1.22 String Format¶

As we learned in the Python Variables, we cannot combine strings and numbers. But we can combine strings and numbers using the format() method!

The format() method takes the passed arguments, formats them, and places them in the string where the Brace placeholders {} are:

Use the format() method to insert numbers into strings:

In [46]:
age = 2025
txt = "We are the DAE student, and we are the class of {}"
print(txt.format(age))

We are the DAE student, and we are the class of 2025

The format() method takes unlimited number of arguments, and are placed into the respective placeholders:

In [47]:
quantity = 3
itemno = 567
price = 49.95
myorder = "I want {} pieces of item {} for {} dollars."
print(myorder.format(quantity, itemno, price))

I want 3 pieces of item 567 for 49.95 dollars.

You can use index numbers {0} to be sure the arguments are placed in the correct placeholders:

In [48]:
quantity = 3
itemno = 567
price = 49.95
myorder = "I want to pay {2} dollars for {0} pieces of item {1}."
print(myorder.format(quantity, itemno, price))

I want to pay 49.95 dollars for 3 pieces of item 567.

Exercise 1.23 Escape Character¶

To insert characters that are illegal in a string, use an escape character.

An escape character is a backslash \ followed by the character you want to insert.

An example of an illegal character is a double quote inside a string that is surrounded by double quotes. You will get an error if you use double quotes inside a string that is surrounded by double quotes.

To fix this problem, use the escape character \":

In [49]:
txt = "We are the so-called \"Husky\" at Northeastern University."
print(txt)

We are the so-called "Husky" at Northeastern University.

4. Python Booleans¶

Booleans represent one of two values: True or False.

Exercise 1.24 Boolean Values¶

In programming you often need to know if an expression is True or False.

You can evaluate any expression in Python, and get one of two answers, True or False.

When you compare two values, the expression is evaluated and Python returns the Boolean answer:

In [50]:

Out[50]:
False
In [51]:
x="aBC"
y="ABC"
x==y
Out[51]:
False
In [52]:
# Createing X variable where x = 2
x=2
In [53]:

Out[53]:
False
In [54]:
x<1 and x==3
Out[54]:
False
In [55]:
x<1 or x==2
Out[55]:
True
In [56]:
x=1
y=2
x is y
Out[56]:
False
In [57]:
x="abcd"
y="abc"
x in y
Out[57]:
False

Python divides the operators in the following groups:

  • Arithmetic operators
  • Assignment operators
  • Comparison operators
  • Logical operators
  • Identity operators
  • Membership operators
  • Bitwise operators

Arithmetic operators are used with numeric values to perform common mathematical operations:

6. Python Lists¶

Lists are used to store multiple items in a single variable.

Lists are one of 4 built-in data types in Python used to store collections of data, the other 3 are Tuple, Set, and Dictionary, all with different qualities and usage.

Lists are created using square brackets:

Exercise 1.28 Creating a list¶

List items are ordered, changeable, and allow duplicate values.

List items are indexed, the first item has index [0], the second item has index [1] etc.

In [68]:
thislist = [100,200,300,400,500,600,700,800,900]
print(thislist)

[100, 200, 300, 400, 500, 600, 700, 800, 900]

When we say that lists are ordered, it means that the items have a defined order, and that order will not change.

If you add new items to a list, the new items will be placed at the end of the list.

In [69]:
thislist = ["apple", "banana", "cherry"]
print(thislist)

['apple', 'banana', 'cherry']
In [70]:
thislist = ["apple", "banana", "cherry"]
type(thislist)
Out[70]:
list
In [71]:
thislist = [1,2,3]
type(thislist)
Out[71]:
list

Exercise 1.29 Allow Duplicates¶

Since lists are indexed, lists can have items with the same value:

In [72]:
thislist = ["apple", "banana", "cherry", "apple", "cherry"]
print(thislist)

['apple', 'banana', 'cherry', 'apple', 'cherry']

Exercise 1.30 List Length¶

To determine how many items a list has, use the len() function:

Print the number of items in the list:

In [73]:
thislist = ["apple", "banana", "cherry"]
print(len(thislist))

3

Exercise 1.31 List Items - Data Types¶

List items can be of any data type:

String, int and boolean data types:

In [74]:
list1 = ["apple", "banana", "cherry"]
print(list1)

['apple', 'banana', 'cherry']
In [75]:
list2 = [1, 5, 7, 9, 3]
print(list2)

[1, 5, 7, 9, 3]
In [76]:
list3 = [True, False, False]
print(list3)

[True, False, False]

A list can contain different data types:

In [77]:
list4 = ["abc", 34, True, 40, "male"]
print(list4)

['abc', 34, True, 40, 'male']

Exercise 1.32 Access List Items¶

List items are indexed and you can access them by referring to the index number:

In [78]:
thislist = ["apple", "banana", "cherry"]
print(thislist[1])

banana

Note that The first item has an index 0.

Negative Indexing:¶

Negative indexing means start from the end

-1 refers to the last item, -2 refers to the second last item etc.

In [79]:
thislist = ["apple", "banana", "cherry"]
print(thislist[-1])

cherry

Printed the last item of the list.

Range of Indexes¶

You can specify a range of indexes by specifying where to start and where to end the range.

When specifying a range, the return value will be a new list with the specified items.

In [80]:
thislist = ["apple", "banana", "cherry", "orange", "kiwi", "melon", "mango"]
print(thislist[2:5])

['cherry', 'orange', 'kiwi']

Returned the third, fourth, and fifth item. Note that the search started at index 2 (included) and end at index 5 (not included).

By leaving out the start value, the range will start at the first item:

This example returns the items from the beginning to, but NOT including, index 5 "melon":

In [81]:
thislist = ["apple", "banana", "cherry", "orange", "kiwi", "melon", "mango"]
print(thislist[:5])

['apple', 'banana', 'cherry', 'orange', 'kiwi']

By leaving out the end value, the range will go on to the end of the list:

This example returns the items from "cherry" to the end:

In [82]:
thislist = ["apple", "banana", "cherry", "orange", "kiwi", "melon", "mango"]
print(thislist[2:])

['cherry', 'orange', 'kiwi', 'melon', 'mango']

Range of Negative Indexes¶

Specify negative indexes if you want to start the search from the end of the list:

In [83]:
thislist = ["apple", "banana", "cherry", "orange", "kiwi", "melon", "mango"]
print(thislist[-4:-1])

['orange', 'kiwi', 'melon']

This example returns the items from "orange" (-4) to, but NOT including "mango" (-1):

Exercise 1.33 Check if Item Exists¶

To determine if a specified item is present in a list use the in keyword:

Check if "apple" is present in the list:

In [84]:
thislist = ["apple", "banana", "cherry"]
if "apple" in thislist:
    print("Yes, 'apple' is in the fruits list")

Yes, 'apple' is in the fruits list

Exercise 1.34 Change Item Value¶

To change the value of a specific item, refer to the index number:

Change the second item:

In [85]:
thislist = ["apple", "banana", "cherry"]
thislist[1] = "blackcurrant"
print(thislist)

['apple', 'blackcurrant', 'cherry']

Change a Range of Item Values¶

To change the value of items within a specific range, define a list with the new values, and refer to the range of index numbers where you want to insert the new values:

Change the values "banana" and "cherry" with the values "blackcurrant" and "watermelon":

In [86]:
thislist = ["apple", "banana", "cherry", "orange", "kiwi", "mango"]
thislist[1:3] = ["blackcurrant", "watermelon"]
print(thislist)

['apple', 'blackcurrant', 'watermelon', 'orange', 'kiwi', 'mango']

If you insert more items than you replace, the new items will be inserted where you specified, and the remaining items will move accordingly:

Change the second value by replacing it with two new values:

In [87]:
thislist = ["apple", "banana", "cherry"]
thislist[1:2] = ["blackcurrant", "watermelon"]
print(thislist)

['apple', 'blackcurrant', 'watermelon', 'cherry']

Note that the length of the list will change when the number of items inserted does not match the number of items replaced.

If you insert less items than you replace, the new items will be inserted where you specified, and the remaining items will move accordingly:

Change the second and third value by replacing it with one value:

In [88]:
thislist = ["apple", "banana", "cherry"]
thislist[1:3] = ["watermelon"]
print(thislist)

['apple', 'watermelon']

Exercise 1.35 Insert Items¶

To insert a new list item, without replacing any of the existing values, we can use the insert() method.

The insert() method inserts an item at the specified index:

Insert "watermelon" as the third item:

In [89]:
thislist = ["apple", "banana", "cherry"]
thislist.insert(2, "watermelon")
print(thislist)

['apple', 'banana', 'watermelon', 'cherry']

As a result, the list will now contain 4 items.

Exercise 1.36 Extend List¶

To append elements from another list to the current list, use the extend() method.

Add the elements of tropical to thislist:

In [90]:
thislist = ["apple", "banana", "cherry"]
tropical = ["mango", "pineapple", "papaya"]
thislist.extend(tropical)
print(thislist)

['apple', 'banana', 'cherry', 'mango', 'pineapple', 'papaya']

The elements will be added to the end of the list.

Exercise 1.37 Remove Specified Item¶

The remove() method removes the specified item.

In [91]:
thislist = ["apple", "banana", "cherry"]
thislist.remove("banana")
print(thislist)

['apple', 'cherry']

Removed "banana"

If there are more than one item with the specified value, the remove() method removes the first occurance:

In [92]:
thislist = ["apple", "banana", "cherry", "banana", "kiwi"]
thislist.remove("banana")
print(thislist)

['apple', 'cherry', 'banana', 'kiwi']

Removed the first occurance of "banana"

Exercise 1.38 Remove Specified Index¶

The pop() method removes the specified index.

Remove the second item:

In [93]:
thislist = ["apple", "banana", "cherry"]
thislist.pop(1)
print(thislist)

['apple', 'cherry']

If you do not specify the index, the pop() method removes the last item.

In [94]:
thislist = ["apple", "banana", "cherry"]
thislist.pop()
print(thislist)

['apple', 'banana']

Removed the last item!

The del keyword can also delete the list completely.

In [95]:
thislist = ["apple", "banana", "cherry"]
del thislist
In [96]:
#print(thislist)

Exercise 1.40 Clear the List¶

The clear() method empties the list.

The list still remains, but it has no content.

In [97]:
thislist = ["apple", "banana", "cherry"]
thislist.clear()
print(thislist)

[]

Exercise 1.41 Sort Lists¶

List objects have a sort() method that will sort the list alphanumerically, ascending, by default.

Sort the list alphabetically:

In [98]:
thislist = ["orange", "mango", "kiwi", "pineapple", "banana"]
thislist.sort()
print(thislist)

['banana', 'kiwi', 'mango', 'orange', 'pineapple']

Sort the list numerically:

In [99]:
thislist = [100, 50, 65, 82, 23]
thislist.sort()
print(thislist)

[23, 50, 65, 82, 100]

Sort Descending¶

To sort descending, use the keyword argument reverse = True:

In [100]:
thislist = ["orange", "mango", "kiwi", "pineapple", "banana"]
thislist.sort(reverse = True)
print(thislist)

['pineapple', 'orange', 'mango', 'kiwi', 'banana']
In [101]:
thislist = [100, 50, 65, 82, 23]
thislist.sort(reverse = True)
print(thislist)

[100, 82, 65, 50, 23]

Exercise 1.42 Reverse Order¶

The reverse() method reverses the current sorting order of the elements.

In [102]:
thislist = ["banana", "Orange", "Kiwi", "cherry"]
thislist.reverse()
print(thislist)

['cherry', 'Kiwi', 'Orange', 'banana']

Exercise 1.43 Copy a List¶

You cannot copy a list simply by typing list2 = list1, because: list2 will only be a reference to list1, and changes made in list1 will automatically also be made in list2.

There are ways to make a copy, one way is to use the built-in List method copy().

Make a copy of a list with the copy() method:

In [103]:
thislist = ["apple", "banana", "cherry"]
mylist = thislist.copy()
print(mylist)

['apple', 'banana', 'cherry']

Another way to make a copy is to use the built-in method list().

In [104]:
thislist = ["apple", "banana", "cherry"]
mylist = list(thislist)
print(mylist)

['apple', 'banana', 'cherry']

Exercise 1.44 Join Lists¶

There are several ways to join, or concatenate, two or more lists in Python.

One of the easiest ways are by using the + operator.

In [105]:
list1 = ["a", "b", "c"]
list2 = [1, 2, 3]

list3 = list1 + list2
print(list3)

['a', 'b', 'c', 1, 2, 3]

Another way to join two lists is by appending all the items from list2 into list1, one by one:

Append list2 into list1:

In [106]:
list1 = ["a", "b" , "c"]
list2 = [1, 2, 3]

for x in list2:
    list1.append(x)

print(list1)

['a', 'b', 'c', 1, 2, 3]

Or you can use the extend() method, where the purpose is to add elements from one list to another list:

In [107]:
list1 = ["a", "b" , "c"]
list2 = [1, 2, 3]

list1.extend(list2)
print(list1)

['a', 'b', 'c', 1, 2, 3]
